If we stop treating hierarchy ↔ anarchy as a single line and instead ask, “What are the possible ways independent agents coordinate?” the space gets much richer.

Some of the major regions are:

Region	Primary coordinating mechanism
Hierarchy	Authority
Anarchy	Local autonomy
Market	Exchange
Democracy	Voting
Meritocracy	Demonstrated competence
Technocracy	Expertise
Bureaucracy	Rules and procedure
Network	Relationships
Protocol	Shared interfaces
Ecology	Feedback and adaptation
Culture	Shared norms
Tradition	Inherited behavior
Religion	Shared sacred commitments
Family	Kinship
Tribe	Identity
Reputation	Social memory
Reciprocity	Mutual obligation
Contracts	Explicit agreements
Algorithms	Computation
Physics	Natural law
Evolution	Selection over time

Notice these aren’t just political systems.

They’re coordination mechanisms.

